The Decision Filter Manual
Implementation Guide
How to classify decision noise, install boundaries, and reduce escalation load.

Document Type: Implementation Guide
Title: The Decision Filter Manual
Author: AI Virtual Agency
Contact: biztechwellnessai@gmail.com
Website: www.aivirtualagency.com

Purpose
The Decision Filter is a repeatable workflow that turns messy inbound “decision noise” (Slack, email threads, meeting notes, approvals) into:
- A Green / Yellow / Red decision routing list
- A short list of installable boundary rules
- A conservative time-reclaim estimate tied to the decisions removed from escalation

Who uses it
- Founders
- Executive/Admin assistants
- Ops managers
- Team leads

What it solves
- Repeated approvals
- “Quick questions” that interrupt flow
- Unclear thresholds that force escalation
- Decision fatigue and context switching

Inputs the Decision Filter accepts
Paste any of the following:
- Slack thread(s) or “Can I…?” messages
- Email chain(s)
- Meeting notes
- Approval lists (“approved this / reviewed that / signed off”)
- Task lists with questions embedded

Minimum requirement
At least 20 lines of real messages/notes, or 10 decisions.

Output schema (must be consistent)
Decision Routing Table
Each item outputs:
- Decision summary (plain language)
- Category: Green / Yellow / Red
- Reason (why it belongs there)
- Suggested boundary rule (if Green or Yellow)
- Escalation rule (if Red)
- Estimated time saved per week (conservative)

Boundary Rule Drafts
Provide 3–7 rules in this format:
- Rule name
- What is allowed
- Threshold
- Owner
- What to do when unclear
- Escalation condition

How classification works
Green (Move without asking)
Decisions that should be handled by the team under a clear rule.
Examples: Spend approvals under a threshold, Scheduling within defined constraints, Standard client requests already in scope.

Yellow (Move and notify)
The team acts, but the decision-maker gets a notification summary.
Examples: Minor client changes that impact timeline but not scope, Vendor adjustments under a limit, Exceptions that occur occasionally.

Red (Escalate)
True risk, true leverage, or irreversible decisions.
Examples: Legal exposure, Reputation risk, Contract scope change above threshold, Price changes outside approved bands.

The installation steps (the “manual”)
Step 1: Collect Decision Noise (10 minutes)
Step 2: Run the Decision Filter (5 minutes)
Step 3: Choose 1 Boundary to Install Today (10 minutes)
Step 4: Install the Boundary (15 minutes)
Step 5: Enforce for 7 days

Time reclaim estimate model (simple + believable)
Weekly time reclaimed = prevented_escalations * minutes_per_escalation
Recommended default: 5 minutes per prevented escalation.

What “good” looks like in week 1
By day 7 you should have: 1–3 boundaries installed, Fewer interruptions, A clearer escalation standard, A record of prevented escalations.

Common failure modes (and fixes)
Failure: Rule is vague. Fix: add thresholds and examples.
Failure: Team still escalates. Fix: make the boundary visible + redirect questions back to the rule.
Failure: Founder overrides. Fix: change language from blame to structure.

Quick templates
Boundary Rule Template: Rule Name, Scope, Threshold(s), Owner, Allowed Actions, Notify, Escalate When, Examples.
Escalation Rule Template: Escalate if, Who decides, Required context, Decision timeframe.
